  Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2t4ln DW contacted the Spanish Ministry of the Interior to confirm if the number of Venezuelan women victims of sexual trafficking is indeed on the rise, but had not received a response at the time of publication. Cendon added that, makes matters worse, seeking asylum in Europe generally has been marred by obstacles. "The fact that certain countries have blocked the possibility of seeking asylum at their embassies is having the effect of increasing human trafficking," she argued. The Spanish Law of Asylum passed in 2009 presents a paradox: legally, it guarantees asylum seekers the right of passage from their country of origin to Spain in order to formally request asylum, but lawmakers have not yet written the legal terms and conditions for this to happen. Thus, while asylum seekers have a legal right to be provided with safe passage, there is no procedure with which to carry this out. In the end, they have to find a way to flee on their own and this is where the human trafficking organizations lure them in. Read more: Follow the money: What are the EU's migration policy priorities? Combatting trafficking 'the state's responsibility' One of the biggest obstacles to tackling the reality of sexual exploitation or other kinds of human trafficking is understanding the scope of the problem. SICAR Cat charges that while Spain in principle guarantees basic rights to people who have been victims of trafficking, the government only speaks of about 14,000 "potential victims" of sexual trafficking overall, and of those only 50 foreign victims per year are recognized and granted basic rights including a living and working permit. The organization calls this number "ridiculous" and argues that this wide gap is a result of government inaction. Human trafficking is considered to be the "second most lucrative" practice worldwide and while the Spanish government pledges funds to fight it, Cendon says the amount the government provides is nowhere near adequate; her organization argues that much more resources for protection of victims and persecution of criminals are needed, as well as education and development funds. Ultimately, the organization decried that this delicate issue has been left mostly to be dealt with by NGOs. "Human trafficking is a violation of human rights and as such it is the state's responsibility," Cendon affirmed. Send  Facebook   Twitter   Google+   Whatsapp   
